{
  "query": "How do long-term and temporary fishery closures compare in their effects on marine fish abundance?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from fishery closure studies, long-term and temporary fishery closures show markedly different effects on marine fish abundance. Long-term fishery closures demonstrated more positive outcomes, with two site comparison studies finding higher abundance of fish species in areas closed to groundfish fisheries for six to eight years compared to open areas (Action 2655). Additionally, one study found more young salmon returning to rivers in the five years after long-term closure of a commercial coastal fishery (Action 2655). In contrast, temporary fishery closures showed limited or no positive effects on fish abundance. One before-and-after, site comparison study in the Atlantic Ocean found no increase in the biomass of the spawning stock of cod following a temporary fishery closure compared to fished areas over nine years (Action 2664). Similarly, the same study found no change in cod catches following temporary fishery closure compared to fished areas (Action 2664). The evidence suggests that while long-term closures can lead to increased fish abundance and biomass in protected areas, temporary closures may not provide sufficient time for fish populations to recover and show measurable increases in abundance.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2664",
    "2655"
  ]
}

