{
  "query": "What are the observed effects on fish abundance and diversity from prohibiting most or all fishing within Marine Protected Areas?",
  "relevant_summary": "Marine Protected Areas that prohibit most or all fishing show significant positive effects on fish abundance and diversity based on extensive research evidence. Regarding fish abundance, 30 of 54 site comparison studies found that marine protected areas prohibiting all fishing for up to 25 years or more had higher abundances (density and/or biomass) of all fish, fishery targeted fish species, non-fishery targeted fish species, and all or most individual fish species/groups monitored compared to unprotected fished areas (Action ID: 2682). Five of six reviews across the world found that non-fished marine reserves with one to 27 years of protection had higher abundances of all fish and all fish and invertebrates combined compared to fished areas (Action ID: 2682). Two systematic reviews found that marine protected areas prohibiting all fishing had greater overall invertebrate abundance and biomass compared to fished areas (Action ID: 2224).\n\nFor fish diversity and species richness, 14 of 20 site comparison studies found that marine protected areas that had prohibited all fishing for between one to more than 25 years had higher fish species richness compared to fished areas (Action ID: 2682). However, six studies found similar fish species richness between one and 20 years after all fishing was banned in protected areas compared to fished areas, and one systematic review found no difference in species richness between unfished protected areas and fished areas (Action ID: 2682). One study found higher number of fish species in the no-fishing/no access zone of a multi-zoned marine protected area compared to partially fished zones and unprotected fished areas 10 to 15 years after implementation (Action ID: 2674).\n\nThe research also shows that fish in protected areas are larger than those in fished areas. Two global review studies and two systematic reviews found that prohibiting all fishing in marine protected areas for one to 27 years resulted in larger fish overall compared to fished areas (Action ID: 2682). Eight of 11 site comparison studies found that non-fished protected areas had larger fish overall and larger individuals of all or most fish species/groups monitored compared to fished areas, after one to 22 years (Action ID: 2682).\n\nCommunity composition changes were also observed, with seven site comparison studies finding that protected areas where all fishing had been prohibited for between three and 16 years had different fish community composition compared to fished areas (Action ID: 2682).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2682",
    "2224",
    "2674",
    "2681"
  ]
}

