{
  "query": "What are the comparative effects on fish abundance of prohibiting all static fishing gear versus prohibiting only line fishing?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, there are limited direct comparative studies between prohibiting all static fishing gear versus prohibiting only line fishing. \n\nProhibiting all static fishing gear: One study in the Coral Sea (Australia) found that areas closed to non-towed fishing gears had higher overall shark abundance when sampled with longlines but not gillnets compared to areas where commercial gillnets were permitted (action 2670). The same study found that shark length was greater for two of five species/groups, similar for two and dependent on sampling gear for one species in closed areas compared to areas where commercial gillnets were permitted.\n\nProhibiting only line fishing: One study in the Indian Ocean (South Africa) found that prohibiting offshore line fishing and all other boat-based fishing in a marine protected area zone resulted in higher abundances of four of four fish species over-exploited by line fishing, compared to two zones where boat-based line and spear fishing was permitted (action 2671). The same study found that four of four fish species over-exploited by line fishing were larger in the protected zone closed for two to seven years.\n\nThe evidence suggests both approaches can increase fish abundance, but the studies examined different fish groups (sharks for static gear prohibition, line-targeted species for line fishing prohibition) and different geographic regions, making direct comparison difficult based on available data.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2670",
    "2671"
  ]
}

