{
  "query": "What are the outcomes for fish populations when marine protected areas are managed with zonation systems that permit some fishing?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, marine protected areas with zonation systems that permit some fishing show variable outcomes for fish populations depending on the level of restrictions in different zones. In MPAs with zonation systems, fish abundance and biomass varied with the level of restriction between zones, with non-fished zones (no-entry and no-take) showing higher density, biomass, and abundance of fish compared to fished zones inside areas protected for 10 to 27 years, though effects varied between fish feeding groups, zone protection level, and reef region (Action 2674). Fish abundance and size were generally largest within no-take zones compared to partially fished zones within the same MPA system (Action 2674).\n\nRegarding fish diversity, one study found a higher number of fish species in the no-fishing/no access zone of a multi-zoned marine protected area compared to two partially fished zones and unprotected fished areas 10 to 15 years after implementation (Action 2674). Fish size outcomes showed that controlling human activity in marine protected areas with zonation systems resulted in larger average lengths of steentjies and three seabream species compared to unprotected fished areas, with lengths being largest within a no-take zone than a partially fished zone (Action 2674). Additionally, larger sizes were found for four of four coral reef fish in zones where nearly all fishing is prohibited compared to adjacent zones with fewer fishing restrictions two to seven years after protection (Action 2674).\n\nFish movement patterns indicated that most individuals of reef fish species tagged and released inside protected areas were recaptured again at almost the same locations over four to nine years, mainly in zones where all or nearly all fishing was prohibited, indicating increased protection from fishing (Action 2674). However, one study found that restricting all fishing activity except for bait fishing in marine protected areas for seven years resulted in similar total fish biomass and lower total fish density compared to unprotected areas (Action 2681).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2674",
    "2681"
  ]
}

