{
  "query": "How does the effectiveness of prohibiting mobile bottom fishing gear vary between the North Atlantic and other regions like the Mediterranean or Indian Ocean?",
  "relevant_summary": "The effectiveness of prohibiting mobile bottom fishing gear varies between regions, with studies from the North Atlantic, Mediterranean, and Indian Ocean showing different outcomes. In the North Atlantic Ocean, studies found mixed results with one study showing increased total fish biomass after 15 years in areas closed to bottom trawling, while another found no effect on abundance of bottom-dwelling fish species after 10 years (Action 2673). North Atlantic studies also showed no increases in haddock recruitment or survival seven years after bottom trawling closure (Action 2673).\n\nIn the Mediterranean Sea, effectiveness appeared more positive with studies showing higher biomass of adult red mullet after 14 years and increased recruitment of young red mullet after 14 years when areas were closed to bottom-towed fishing gears (Action 2673). The Mediterranean also showed increased adult red mullet sizes after closure (Action 2673). Additionally, Mediterranean studies of bottom trawling prohibitions showed different invertebrate community composition compared to trawled areas after 15-20 years, with mixed results on diversity depending on study duration (Action 2099).\n\nIn the Indian Ocean, results varied significantly between studies and species. One study found increased abundance of long-snouted seahorses but not short-snouted seahorses after one year of prohibiting mobile bottom fishing gears (Action 2673). Another study found that fish catch rates were higher in areas prohibiting seine nets for 3-6 years (Action 2673). Indian Ocean studies of complete commercial fishing bans showed larger overall fish sizes in marine reserves after five years compared to fished areas (Action 2667).\n\nThe evidence suggests that the effectiveness of mobile bottom fishing gear prohibitions may depend on regional factors, species studied, enforcement duration, and specific gear types prohibited, with Mediterranean studies generally showing more consistent positive outcomes than North Atlantic or Indian Ocean studies.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2673",
    "2099",
    "2667"
  ]
}

