{
  "query": "What are the documented effects of modifying fishing trap or pot configurations on marine fish?",
  "relevant_summary": "Twenty-three studies examined the effects of modifying fishing trap or pot configuration on marine fish populations across various global locations including the Atlantic Ocean, Baltic Sea, Mediterranean Sea, Southern Ocean, Tasman Sea, Adriatic Sea, Bothnian Sea, Indian Ocean, Pacific Ocean, the Kattegat and the Barents Sea (action 2702). The documented effects include: survival impacts where one study found that survival of small herring escaped from a pontoon fish trap through a size-sorting grid was similar to trap-caught herring that did not pass through a grid (action 2702). Regarding reduction of unwanted catch, sixteen of 20 studies found that modifications to trap configuration, including using different trap types, increased mesh size and fitting escape devices, reduced unwanted catches of various fish species including brown trout, black sea bass, herring, bluethroat wrasse and leatherjacket, cod, protected rockfishes, whitefish, American eel and winter flounder, and sharks/rays compared to unmodified conventional traps (action 2702). However, three studies found that trap modification had no effect on unwanted catches of white croaker, non-commercial fish or undersized Atlantic cod, and one study found non-target haddock catches were increased (action 2702). For size-selectivity improvements, three of four studies found that traps or pots modified with square mesh escape windows or larger mesh sizes improved size-selectivity of Atlantic cod, black sea bass and most fish species compared to smaller mesh and standard gear, while one study found increasing mesh size of trap escape panels had no effect on size-selectivity of panga (action 2702). Additionally, trap modifications showed effects on marine mammals, with steel rods on lobster pots and metal frames on fishing pots reducing sea lion pup and seal entrapments (action 2822).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2702",
    "2822",
    "2148",
    "2146"
  ]
}

