{"query": "What is the evidence for using electropositive deterrents on fishing gear to reduce unwanted catches of sharks and rays?", "summary": "Nine studies examined the effect of attaching electropositive deterrents to fishing gear on marine fish populations, conducted across the Atlantic Ocean (USA, Canada, Bahamas), Gulf of Alaska (USA), South Pacific Ocean (Australia), Tasman Sea (Australia), and laboratory facilities (USA), plus one global systematic review (Action 2696). 

Regarding behavioral effects, three of four replicated studies found that electropositive deterrent materials attached near bait reduced feeding attempts and bait consumption of spiny dogfish, great hammerhead and draughtboard sharks compared to gear without deterrents, while one study found no reduction in bait consumption by bonnethead and young lemon sharks. Importantly, one study found that commercially valuable Pacific halibut behavior was unaffected by deterrent materials (Action 2696).

For bycatch reduction, two of four replicated, controlled studies in the Gulf of Alaska, Pacific Ocean and Atlantic Ocean found that fishing gear (longlines and traps) fitted with electropositive deterrents caught fewer unwanted spiny dogfish, longnose skate, sharks and rays, and fewer undersized halibut compared to standard fishing gear or gear with non-deterrent materials. However, the other two studies and a global systematic review found that electropositive deterrents resulted in similar catches of unwanted spiny dogfish, total shark catch, blue shark, and total sharks and rays compared to gear with no deterrents (Action 2696).", "action_ids": ["2696"]}

