{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits of ceasing all fishing in a marine protected area on fish community composition and species richness?",
  "relevant_summary": "The documented benefits of ceasing all fishing in marine protected areas on fish community composition and species richness include the following evidence:\n\nCOMMUNITY COMPOSITION: Seven site comparison studies in the Mediterranean Sea, Indian Ocean, Philippine Sea and Atlantic Ocean found that protected areas where all fishing had been prohibited for between three and 16 years had a different fish community composition compared to fished areas (Action 2682). Additionally, three before-and-after studies in the Tasman Sea and South China Sea found that fish assemblage/species composition was different before and after prohibiting all commercial fishing (Action 2667).\n\nSPECIES RICHNESS: Fourteen of 20 site comparison studies in the Indian Ocean, Mediterranean Sea, Philippine Sea, Tasman Sea, Atlantic Ocean, Caribbean Sea, Coral Sea and Pacific Ocean found that marine protected areas that had prohibited all fishing for between one to more than 25 years had higher fish species richness compared to fished areas (Action 2682). However, six studies found similar fish species richness between one and 20 years after all fishing was banned in protected areas compared to fished areas, and one systematic review in the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans found no difference in species richness between unfished protected areas and fished areas (Action 2682). One replicated site comparison study in the Indian Ocean found that the effects of prohibiting all fishing on fish species richness/diversity after 15 years varied with the sampling method used (Action 2682).\n\nCONTRASTING EVIDENCE: One site comparison study in the Caribbean Sea found that in marine protected areas closed to all fishing with limited exceptions for up to seven years, there was lower total fish species richness compared to unprotected areas (Action 2681). One before-and-after study in the South China Sea found that fish species richness decreased in the wider region five years after all commercial fishing was banned in two marine reserves (Action 2667).",
  "action_ids": [
    "2682",
    "2681",
    "2667"
  ]
}

