{
  "query": "How does using a square mesh codend compare to rotating a diamond mesh codend for improving size-selectivity in trawl nets?",
  "relevant_summary": "Both square mesh codends and rotating diamond mesh codends can improve size-selectivity in trawl nets, but they show different effectiveness patterns. Action 2714 found that square mesh codends improved size selectivity for silver hake, horse mackerel, European hake, axillary seabream, poor cod, greater forkbeard, blue whiting, discarded fish and three of four commercially targeted fish compared to diamond mesh codends, while five studies found no difference in size selectivity for Atlantic mackerel, long rough dab, yellowtail scad and striped seapike, rockfish and flatfish, and three of four commercially important bottom fish species. Three studies found that the effect varied with fish body shape, with round-bodied fish showing improved selectivity but not flatfish. Action 2715 found that turning diamond mesh orientation by 90\u00b0 resulted in better size selection of cod, red mullet and common pandora, and round-bodied fish species, but not of plaice, annular sea bream, and flatfish species compared to standard orientation diamond mesh. One study found that turned mesh did not improve size selectivity of cod, plaice and flounder. Action 2714 also found that square mesh codends reduced unwanted catches of all fish species monitored, young individuals of half or most commercially targeted fish, total unwanted catch, and discarded fish in deeper fishing areas compared to diamond mesh codends. Action 2714 reported that fish caught in square mesh codends had higher short-term survival rates for two of six fish species compared to diamond mesh codends.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2714",
    "2715",
    "2724"
  ]
}

