{
  "query": "How do the effects on fish community composition of prohibiting all commercial fishing compare between the Tasman Sea and the South Atlantic Ocean?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents examined, there are notable differences in the effects of prohibiting all commercial fishing on fish community composition between the Tasman Sea and South Atlantic Ocean. In the Tasman Sea, two before-and-after studies found that fish assemblage/species composition was different before and after prohibiting all commercial fishing, with changes observed in an estuary after two years and in the wider region surrounding two marine reserves five years after their creation (Action 2667). Additionally, one before-and-after study in the Tasman Sea found that most fish species in an estuary in a marine reserve had lower abundance two years after it was closed to all commercial fishing than before (Action 2667). In contrast, the South Atlantic Ocean showed different results - one site comparison study found no change in species composition between a reserve closed to all commercial fishing for 40 years and unprotected fished areas (Action 2667). Furthermore, the same South Atlantic Ocean study found no difference in overall fish diversity between the protected area closed to all commercial fishing for 40 years compared to unprotected fished areas (Action 2667). Regarding fish abundance, the South Atlantic Ocean study found that there were higher abundances of one of four commercially targeted fish species in the protected area compared to unprotected fished areas (Action 2667). The key difference appears to be that Tasman Sea studies documented changes in community composition following fishing prohibition, while the South Atlantic Ocean study found no change in composition despite 40 years of protection.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2667"
  ]
}

