{
  "query": "What does the evidence suggest about the timeframe over which prohibiting all fishing in a marine protected area leads to increased fish abundance?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence suggests variable timeframes for fish abundance increases following fishing prohibitions in marine protected areas. Action 2682 found that marine protected areas prohibiting all fishing for 1 to 25 years or more showed higher fish abundances compared to fished areas, with 30 of 54 studies finding positive effects. Some studies found similar abundances between protected and fished areas between 1 and 20 years after implementation. Action 2681 found that restricting all fishing activity in marine protected areas for 1 to 8 years resulted in similar fish abundance and biomass compared to unprotected areas, with one study showing lower total fish density after 7 years. Action 2682 also found that effects varied between fish species and groups, with some studies showing that abundance effects depended on the age of the protected area. One review found that fish abundance in no-take marine reserves 1 to 25 years old was affected by duration of protection among other factors. Action 2674 showed that in zonation systems, fish abundance and biomass increased after 3-15 years compared to unprotected areas. Action 2667 found mixed results, with some areas showing higher abundances after 5 years and 40 years, while others showed no increase 2-13 years after closure.",
  "action_ids": [
