{
  "query": "What is the evidence from global reviews on the effectiveness of catch share systems for managing fish stocks sustainably?",
  "relevant_summary": "According to global reviews, catch share systems show evidence of effectiveness for sustainable fish stock management. Two worldwide systematic reviews examined the effects of introducing catch shares on marine fish populations (action 3812). One review found that fisheries or stocks managed under catch shares were more likely to meet management target levels for biomass sustainability than those that did not meet targets. However, another study found no difference in performance of biomass-based management targets between fisheries under catch shares, fleet-wide catch caps or fishing effort controls (action 3812). Regarding exploitation rates, two worldwide systematic reviews found that catch share fisheries had lower rates of over-exploitation compared to non-catch share fisheries, and a higher proportion of fisheries managed under catch shares either met or exceeded management target levels for rates of exploitation than those that did not meet targets (action 3812). One global systematic review comparing different management approaches found that catch share fisheries performed similarly to fleet-wide catch quotas in terms of reaching biomass-based management targets, and along with catch quota fisheries, fewer catch share stocks were over-exploited than those with effort controls (action 3811).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3812",
    "3811"
  ]
}

