{"query": "What are the observed effects of fitting deterrents, such as lights or electropositive materials, to fishing gear?", "summary": "Electropositive deterrents attached to fishing gear showed mixed results for reducing unwanted catch. Two of four studies found that fishing gear (longlines and traps) fitted with electropositive deterrent materials caught fewer unwanted spiny dogfish, longnose skate, sharks and rays, and fewer undersized halibut, compared to standard fishing gear (Action 2696). However, two other studies and a global systematic review found that electropositive deterrents resulted in similar catches of unwanted spiny dogfish, sharks, blue shark and sharks and rays compared to gear with no deterrents (Action 2696). For behavioral effects, three of four studies found that electropositive materials reduced the frequency of feeding attempts and bait consumption of spiny dogfish, great hammerhead and draughtboard sharks, while one study found no reduction in bait consumption by bonnethead and young lemon sharks (Action 2696).

Artificial lights on fishing gear demonstrated more consistent positive effects. One study found that shrimp trawl nets with artificial lights caught fewer unwanted fish when fitted to the fishing line, but not when fitted to a size-sorting grid (Action 2695). For marine turtles, four controlled studies found that gillnets with LED lights, light sticks or UV lights caught fewer green turtles and loggerhead turtles than nets without lights (Action 3554). One study in the Adriatic Sea found that no loggerhead turtles were caught and died in gillnets with UV lights whereas some did in nets without lights (Action 3554). However, one study found mixed effects of increasing the number of light sticks on longlines on the chance of catching loggerhead and leatherback turtles (Action 3554).

Visual deterrents showed limited effectiveness, with one study finding that gillnets with floating shark shapes attached caught fewer green turtles than unmodified nets, and another study showing mixed effects of shark-shaped and spherical deterrents on loggerhead turtle behaviors (Action 3553).", "action_ids": ["2696","2695","3554","3553"]}

